    <string-array name="tab_layout_tabs_content">
        <item><![CDATA[
        <h1>About Tab components</h1>
        <p>Like other UI components, a Tab component requires a <b>name</b>, a <b>role</b>,
        a <b>value</b> and a <b>state</b>.</p>
        <p>This is to give screen reader users enough information about the type of the component,
        the name of the tab, the position of the current tab and the total number of tabs there are,
        and if the current tab is selected.</p>
        <p>The utterance must announce all of these information.</p>
        <p>Unfortunately, only the state is automatically announced when using TabLayout from support
        design library. It is responsibility of the developer to set each tab a content description that
        announces the required information.</p>
        ]]></item>
        <item><![CDATA[
        <h1>Common mistakes in Tab components</h1>
        <h2>Lack of content description</h2>
        <p>Because this behavior has not yet been implemented by default in the support design library,
        a lot of developers often forget to provide the required content description to each tab.</p>
        <h2>Auto focus</h2>
        <p>A common mistake developers often do is to move the accessibility focus to the content of the
        tab after selecting a tab. Accessibility focus must stay on the tab after being selected.</p>
        ]]></item>
        <item><![CDATA[
        <h1>Learn more about Tab components</h1>
        <p>Look at the source of this activity and see how we\'re setting content description. You can
        extend the TabLayout to provide this behavior by default.</p>
        <p>Look at the <a href="https://developer.android.com/reference/android/support/design/widget/TabLayout.html">TabLayout</a>
        documentation as well as using a <a href="https://developer.android.com/reference/android/widget/TabHost.html">TabHost</a>.</p>
        ]]></item>
    </string-array>

